38
00:04:08,680 --> 00:04:16,680
It's interesting. I have one, my youngest son now is 12 years old and he's a basketball obsessed and he plays with the local AAU basketball team.

39
00:04:17,680 --> 00:04:22,680
And you notice that, I noticed that the best players are the ones who have older brothers who play.

40
00:04:23,680 --> 00:04:27,680
They're the scrappiest or the toughest. They refuse to give up a rebound.

41
00:04:28,680 --> 00:04:41,680
And I think because they've been playing with their older brothers their whole life, they, I mean, the ones that can compete quit and go into another sport and the ones that can become, sort of refuse to give in.

42
00:04:42,680 --> 00:04:52,680
And so on some level, that probably started my skepticism. But then when I was, you know, so I go to journalism school, I get, I want to be an investigative journalist.

43
00:04:53,680 --> 00:04:57,680
I had read All the President's Men by Woodward and Bernstein. I was fascinated by it.

44
00:04:58,680 --> 00:05:13,680
The only job I could get out of journalism school was, well, I had two semi offers. One was at the Dallas Morning News and in 1979 I wasn't willing to move to Dallas.

45
00:05:14,680 --> 00:05:22,680
And the other was at CNN in Atlanta where they didn't allow cigarette smoking in the newsroom and I was a smoker.

46
00:05:23,680 --> 00:05:39,680
So I stayed in New York and took a job with Discover magazine and three or four years in, I did maybe two or three years and I did a piece, reported an article on the Shroud of Turin. Do you remember that?

47
00:05:40,680 --> 00:05:43,680
Of course. I don't remember the piece actually, but I know what the Shroud is.

48
00:05:44,680 --> 00:06:11,680
So at the time, researchers from Los Alamos were taking this high tech imaging equipment to Turin to study the shroud and they had concluded. So this is supposedly the burial shroud of Christ that it appeared in, if I'm remembering this from 40 years ago, it appeared in the historical record right around the 11th or 12th century, right when there's a big market in sort of fake religious artifacts.

49
00:06:12,680 --> 00:06:29,680
So there's a strong prior belief that this is a fake religious artifact, but the Los Alamos researchers take their high tech imaging equipment to Turin and they say, and they get permission from the church to do it and they say that they can't, they can't understand how this was made.

50
00:06:30,680 --> 00:06:33,680
Even though it's also been carbon dated to the 11th or 12th century.

51
00:06:33,680 --> 00:07:01,680
And I remember a Sunday evening I was living in my studio apartment in New York. I was reading their reports that they had published and I forget what it was. It struck me as profoundly unsupported by the data, but I actually called the researcher in Los Alamos at home to say, how could you possibly interpret this from what you did?

52
00:07:02,680 --> 00:07:22,680
And it was just the sort of step one in realizing and maybe because I had gone to Harvard and I'd gone to Stanford and I knew a lot of people who went into science personally, there's nothing fundamentally different about somebody who goes into science and somebody who goes into journalism other than we have sort of different mechanisms of wanting to understand what truth is.

53
00:07:23,680 --> 00:07:26,680
So, and then when I did my first book, which...

54
00:07:27,680 --> 00:07:29,680
I don't remember. I don't remember.

55
00:07:29,680 --> 00:07:37,680
But if he certainly didn't, wasn't able to satisfactorily defend the interpretation.

56
00:07:38,680 --> 00:07:44,680
It was also an interesting conclusion about the observation about negative results, which comes up all the time.

57
00:07:45,680 --> 00:07:58,680
When somebody gets a negative result, when they're unable to determine how the shroud was created, does that mean that the shroud was created by supernatural means that are beyond the ability of the equipment to do that?

58
00:07:59,680 --> 00:08:05,680
And if the detector doesn't mean that the equipment that they used are simply inadequate for doing the job.

59
00:08:06,680 --> 00:08:16,680
And in effect, almost 40 years later, we're having the same debate online this week about the cause of obesity.

60
00:08:17,680 --> 00:08:26,680
Are you doing the right experiments? Have you refuted the hypothesis? Or are the experiments flawed? And that's always a fundamental issue in science.

61
00:08:26,680 --> 00:08:33,680
Let me ask you a question, sort of tangential. Did you know the harm of cigarette smoking when you were a smoker?

62
00:08:34,680 --> 00:08:42,680
