68
00:09:40,680 --> 00:09:55,680
And I didn't handle that well. So I started smoking, too, I don't know, maybe despite the kids who seemed so happy and complacent in the Stanford sunshine when I was definitely not happy and complacent.

69
00:09:56,680 --> 00:10:08,680
And then it took me 20 years to quit. But, you know, I don't know if children, and we discussed this when we were doing Newsy, I don't know if kids ever think in terms of the things that they do.

70
00:10:09,680 --> 00:10:14,680
They do being dangerous. We both did some very dangerous things when we were younger. We were both boxers.

71
00:10:15,680 --> 00:10:24,680
Although I, this sounds really dumb. And I want to actually talk about your boxing history because the article you wrote in Playboy is such a great one.

72
00:10:25,680 --> 00:10:34,680
But I don't know if I ever told you this story, but the entire time I was boxing, I never thought it was dangerous. I had this true mental block that was I don't get hit.

73
00:10:34,680 --> 00:10:53,680
So it's I'm it's not dangerous. Like nothing's happening to me. You know, I'm evading and I'm hitting and da da da da da, which, of course, was categorically untrue because my style of boxing was actually to get hit, tire out opponents and eventually overcome them due to superior conditioning.

74
00:10:54,680 --> 00:11:06,680
But it never seemed to hurt. And it wasn't until I suffered a very, very severe concussion when I was 20 in this. I still remember it very well. I was actually hospitalized for two days.

75
00:11:07,680 --> 00:11:19,680
Had a CT scan, had significant bruising, had significant cerebral contusions and had a headache that lasted for three months. I mean, this was a real this was the hardest I've ever had my bell rung.

76
00:11:20,680 --> 00:11:35,680
And it was only at that point that I thought, oh, my God, you actually get hit in this sport. And by that point, I'd already decided I didn't want to be a professional boxer. That was the irony of it. I was already in college and I was now only boxing as, you know, something fun to do.

77
00:11:36,680 --> 00:11:47,680
But it literally took that event for me to go. This sport is crazy. And from that point on, I always look at it very differently. But while I was doing it, I never thought that.

78
00:11:48,680 --> 00:11:52,680
I only got into it competitively after my best friend got killed boxing.

79
00:11:53,680 --> 00:11:54,680
So say more about that.

80
00:11:55,680 --> 00:12:11,680
Yeah, well, so, yeah, I mean, there's a lot of things. I was a football player in high school and college. And when you're a football player in high school and college, you know, back then getting your bell rung was not, you know, it just was what it was. I mean, I clearly had at least one concussion in high school football.

81
00:12:11,680 --> 00:12:34,680
My best friend in college who was actually a lot of kids best friends, a very charming, wonderful young man of Puerto Rican descent from New York was an amateur boxer in New York, went back to boxing after his football career, came to an end due to knee injuries and got our senior year.

82
00:12:35,680 --> 00:12:39,680
He had his first fight and he got killed in the ring. He was knocked out. His head hit the mat.

83
00:12:40,680 --> 00:12:59,680
We were in Lowell, Massachusetts, watching the fight at the time. And, you know, he never woke up. They my memory is of them unplugging him a week later. It did not stop me from then moving to New York when school was over. Actually, three years later, when I got to New York, starting to box because I was bored.

84
00:13:00,680 --> 00:13:02,680
Did you think about him?

85
00:13:03,680 --> 00:13:19,680
When I did it? Yeah, sure. But I never thought that what happened to him could happen to me until I got knocked out in my in the Golden Gloves, at which point there's this awareness when you get knocked unconscious, when you wake up that there you there may have.

86
00:13:20,680 --> 00:13:28,680
Some people never wake up from that, that that might have been the moment at which your candle was blown out in effect and there's no relighting it.

87
00:13:29,680 --> 00:13:43,680
But it's, you know, talking about this is interesting because we, you know, a lot of what we do in life and talk about when you're talking about prevention of chronic illnesses and prevention of disease and prevention of addiction.

88
00:13:44,680 --> 00:13:52,680
It's getting young men and women who don't think and don't process risk the same way we do as we get older.

89
00:13:53,680 --> 00:13:59,680
I always thought it was fascinating that the older we get and the less life we have, less to live, the more risk adverse we become.

90
00:14:00,680 --> 00:14:14,680
If something bad happens, you're actually losing less of your life than you are when you're younger. And I'm sure that, you know, behavioral psychologists like Kahneman and Furski could say things or do say things about that.

91
00:14:15,680 --> 00:14:30,680
Tell me about the Playboy article that you wrote after that Golden Gloves tournament. I know you still have at least the last time I was at your house, which maybe eight years ago, you actually had a framed photo of you lying prostrate in the ring.

92
00:14:31,680 --> 00:14:44,680
You know, I still do. And it's in our coat entryway. I often thought of, you know, putting it up here instead of this picture because I refer to it as my hubris protection.

93
00:14:46,680 --> 00:14:53,680
So while I was working at Discover magazine and I was boxing, so this was 1983, 84.

94
00:14:54,680 --> 00:15:04,680
By the way, not too long after Duck Who Kim was killed by Ray Mancini, I mean, the early 80s was a very difficult period in boxing. There were a number of high profile deaths in the ring.

95
00:15:05,680 --> 00:15:20,680
Yeah, he was killed while I was boxing. And we actually did a story on it at Discover about what happens to the brain. I remember there's a good friend of mine, a New York Times reporter now named Denise Grady was writing that story.

96
00:15:20,680 --> 00:15:38,680
And while I was, you know, boxing and getting ready to box in the Golden Gloves and she would come in and slip like, you know, articles under my door about whatever we were calling the traumatic event back then.

97
00:15:39,680 --> 00:16:00,680
Yeah, I was just a young man. I was boxing. I had a friend, a good friend who was Norman Mahler's nephew. And then Norman Mahler had a group of young men, not even that young, who met at a gym that's no longer there on 14th Street in Manhattan back when that was a very questionable part of town.

98
00:16:01,680 --> 00:16:15,680
And we would go down, I think it was every Saturday morning and we would box for a few hours and then we would go out to lunch. And yeah, from that I got the idea, why don't I write boxing the Golden Gloves and write about it?

99
00:16:15,680 --> 00:16:34,680
So I originally was doing it for Sports Illustrated, but then I realized that I was technically too old to do it, that I missed the cutoff by about two or three months and that if I wanted to box, I would have to, let's say, revise my birth certificate.

100
00:16:35,680 --> 00:16:46,680
And so when I realized that I talked to the editors at Sports Illustrated and I said, you folks, you do investigative journalism. We were in the same building, Discover and Sports Illustrated, we're both owned by Time Incorporated at the time.

101
00:16:47,680 --> 00:17:01,680
So I told the editors, you do, you know, hard-hitting investigative journalism. And, you know, if I want to continue to do this article, I'm going to have to fake my age. And I think that's a problem. And the editor has said, well, it is now that you told us.

102
00:17:02,680 --> 00:17:24,680
So we pulled it from Sports Illustrated and one of the editors I worked with had a good friend at Playboy. So I pitched it to Playboy and my sister-in-law got angry at me for writing for a magazine that doesn't portray women in the most ideal light or depending on how you look at it.

103
00:17:25,680 --> 00:17:39,680
And she had a point, but I said some of the best writers in America write for Playboy. And maybe later I'll have the, you know, the platform by which I can be too good for this approach. Anyway, we did it.

104
00:17:39,680 --> 00:17:54,680
I won my first fight against a policeman from Staten Island who beat the crap out of me in the first round. And then I realized that if I punched back, that might help. And I knocked him out in the second round.

105
00:17:55,680 --> 00:18:08,680
And then the second fight was a week later and I got knocked out, I think, a minute and 37 seconds by the fellow who ended up winning our division, who was not particularly good, but I had never really had enough time to work on defense.

106
00:18:09,680 --> 00:18:19,680
I've been boxing for many years, competitively. I had been doing this for about four months at any level other than a Saturday morning hobby.

107
00:18:20,680 --> 00:18:27,680
But it was a reminder that any time I think I'm, you know, we all, some of us grow up with this kind of James Bond complex.

108
00:18:28,680 --> 00:18:41,680
You know, I think it's fair to say between the watches and the fast cars and the archery and things like that, you might have it also that we think we're so cool. We can do anything. And that was my reminder that I'm certainly not.

109
00:18:42,680 --> 00:18:48,680
And that there are things I should stay away from if I want to have a long and healthy life.

110
00:18:49,680 --> 00:18:54,680
Among them being boxing and I haven't gone back and then never went back into the ring after that.

111
00:18:55,680 --> 00:19:09,680
What's the process like of learning to write? I was rereading an article yesterday that you had recently written. And don't get too flattered by this, but I forgot how well you write.

112
00:19:10,680 --> 00:19:22,680
You know, one of the things that I think I write reasonably well. I've learned to write better over the years. And I think a lot of that came from how often I used to write and how often you used to rip what I used to write apart.

113
00:19:23,680 --> 00:19:33,680
You know, back when we were at Newsy, I was doing so much of the writing and you were doing so much of the editing and revising of internal stuff that I would write. And that process, of course, I think made me much better.

114
00:19:34,680 --> 00:19:45,680
And I can now see it when I look at the writing of other people. But you know, your writing today, I think, is really excellent. At least it's a style that I find really good, right? You can write about science in a way that's very readable.

115
00:19:46,680 --> 00:20:03,680
How does one learn that craft? When you show up at Columbia, which ostensibly is the best journalism school in the country, I assume you're coming in incredibly raw. Did you believe you had some talent, some hidden talent for writing?

116
00:20:04,680 --> 00:20:12,680
Or is that not even a part of what they're selecting at a top journalism school? Is it more the thought process they're selecting for and the writing is the easy thing to teach on top?

117
00:20:13,680 --> 00:20:28,680
Well, I thought I could write because I used to write letters to friends and girlfriends that I thought were clever and they liked. So there was always a sense that somewhere inside me, I was a writer.

118
00:20:29,680 --> 00:20:34,680
When I first started taking writing classes, it was actually at night school at Harvard.

119
00:20:37,680 --> 00:20:56,680
After I got my master's degree from Stanford, I went back to Boston. And I don't even remember what I was doing for a living. But over the course of a semester, I took two writing courses, one taught by a science writer from the Boston Herald, who I later worked with at Discover Magazine.

120
00:20:57,680 --> 00:21:10,680
And one taught by a fiction editor from the Atlantic named Michael Curtis, who had been a roommate of Thomas Pinchon and Dick Farina at Cornell in the early 1960s.

121
00:21:11,680 --> 00:21:21,680
He was already a famous fiction editor at the Atlantic. And the very first article I wrote for him could probably remember the subject if I had to.

122
00:21:21,680 --> 00:21:39,680
But what I do remember is it came back with the words, Pure Isle, written in one inch high letters on the front, underlined twice. And I had a look up Pure Isle, which meant basically childish and amateurish and thoughtless.

123
00:21:40,680 --> 00:21:55,680
And over the course of a semester, Michael Curtis started to hammer me into being a functional writer by constant and relentless criticism of what I did.

124
00:21:56,680 --> 00:22:10,680
And I appreciated, in fact, the Boston Herald science editor was so nice, he would read people's work and he believed you should never say anything negative about their work. And I gained absolutely nothing from being in his class.

125
00:22:11,680 --> 00:22:20,680
And he was a lovely man, but I don't think anyone else did either, except maybe, you know, an unjustified sense of their own talent.

126
00:22:21,680 --> 00:22:27,680
Curtis hammered into me. Then when I got to journalism school, it was just about basically teaching you to write a report.

127
00:22:28,680 --> 00:22:44,680
And so it's a steady learning process. And then as a journalist, when I started Discover, I started as a reporter. So Time Inc. back then had reporters who did the information gathering and then we will write files and the files would be given to the writers and the writers were true craftsmen.

128
00:22:45,680 --> 00:22:56,680
And I started off, I don't know, the first story I remember doing was about some type of particle accelerator at Michigan State.

129
00:22:57,680 --> 00:23:09,680
And I had the writers there, probably, you know, friends who were writers would read this draft and then hammer, you know, just relentlessly critique it.

130
00:23:09,680 --> 00:23:15,680
And so I ended up with something that was worth submitting to the editors and then the editors would do the same thing before it would be published.

131
00:23:16,680 --> 00:23:28,680
And as I became a writer and got older, I did that same thing for other reporters who came in under me. And there are, you know, a few very well respected journalists who I think benefited from me being relentlessly critical.

132
00:23:29,680 --> 00:23:40,680
And then the actual process of writing is just, you know, I told you this years ago, Calvin Trillan, the famous New Yorker writer had a phrase he called the first draft, the vomit out.

133
00:23:41,680 --> 00:23:57,680
Where you just get everything down on paper and it kind of relieves the pressure of the first draft. So you get everything down on paper, the computer, and then you just keep rewriting it and rewriting it and rewriting it until it reads like something I would have wanted to read if it hadn't been written down.

134
00:23:58,680 --> 00:24:02,680
And I think that's what I think is really important by me.

135
00:24:03,680 --> 00:24:17,680
And because I read a lot and I read a lot of, you know, very talented authors, I know what good writing looks like and feels like and you just continue to revise and edit until it gets there. It's...

136
00:24:18,680 --> 00:24:21,680
Who's the best living science writer in your opinion?

137
00:24:21,680 --> 00:24:33,680
In my opinion, um, I don't think I could answer that question. There are a lot of people who have a lot of different skills. It's like saying who's the best living football player or the best...

138
00:24:34,680 --> 00:24:46,680
My 12 year old is always asking me who I think the five best basketball players, you know, is... was Will Chamberlain better than Steph Curry? Well, they were different, right?

139
00:24:46,680 --> 00:24:50,680
There are science journalists.

140
00:24:52,680 --> 00:24:57,680
Jesus, a young man at the Atlantic now whose name I'm going to forget.

141
00:24:58,680 --> 00:25:07,680
Henry, somebody who writes a thoughtful, well-reported article on a different subject every three or four days.

142
00:25:08,680 --> 00:25:22,680
And I often read his stuff and I think, could I have done that when I was his age and, you know, worked 70, 80 hours a week, possibly, but I don't think so. And I don't think I could have done it as well.

143
00:25:23,680 --> 00:25:34,680
When I was growing up, the best out there was Jim Glick, who wrote Remember Chaos and the Feynman biography, the name of which I forget at the moment.

144
00:25:35,680 --> 00:25:45,680
There were a whole series of science journal, a whole, you know, collection of science journalists who came of age in the 1980s when science magazines had first started.

145
00:25:46,680 --> 00:25:52,680
There was a magazine called Science, well, Science 80, then it was Science 81, Science 82. There was Discover.

146
00:25:55,680 --> 00:26:00,680
