01:49:44,680 --> 01:50:00,680
I call up one of the people on the list. This is a former president of the American Heart Association at the University of Alabama, Birmingham. And this person tells me that they can't talk about the paper. Or they'll lose their funding.

523
01:50:00,680 --> 01:50:12,680
And I say it's this, we're talking about a diet trial. The New England Journal of Medicine. Nobody loses their funding for talking about that. It's going to be, it's not going to come out till after the embargo.

524
01:50:12,680 --> 01:50:27,680
The woman, she refuses to talk to me. She won't tell me anything. I said, look, if there's something wrong with this paper, let's go off the record. Not for attribution, like Woodward and Bernstein in the garage with deep throat.

525
01:50:27,680 --> 01:50:35,680
Tell me what's wrong with this paper, what the issue is. Because if you don't tell me, I'll never know when I'll report it incorrectly. She refuses even to do that.

526
01:50:35,680 --> 01:50:52,680
So then I get off the phone with her. I call up one of the people that Larry Appel at Johns Hopkins has given me. And he's a researcher who starts yelling at me. This guy is the grand old man of the field. I don't know this.

527
01:50:52,680 --> 01:51:05,680
And he starts yelling at me over the phone that there's no controversy over salt and blood pressure. And I say, I'm not calling about salt and blood pressure professor. I'm calling about this diet trial that lowered blood pressure in the New England Journal of Medicine.

528
01:51:05,680 --> 01:51:21,680
And he continues to berate me that there's no controversy. So I get off the phone with him and I call up my editor at Science. I said I had an American Heart Association former president refused to talk to me because she would lose her funding, she said, if she did.

529
01:51:21,680 --> 01:51:37,680
And then I had this other guy yelling at me that there's no controversy over salt and blood pressure when I'm not writing about salt and blood pressure. There must be a controversy about salt and blood pressure that I know nothing about.

530
01:51:37,680 --> 01:51:48,680
So I'm going to write up this article, get my paycheck, and then if you don't mind, I'm going to look into the assumed salt blood pressure controversy and see what we're missing.

531
01:51:48,680 --> 01:51:58,680
And I spent the next nine months reporting that. I interviewed about 85 people for one magazine article. Turns out that it is one of the most vitriolic controversies in the history of medicine.

532
01:51:58,680 --> 01:52:12,680
And even though already by 1998 we'd all been eating low salt diets in America for 15 to 20 years, it was clear that the randomized control evidence never really supported the intervention.

533
01:52:12,680 --> 01:52:24,680
And that it was backed up by a lot of bad epidemiology and researchers assuming that associations were causal that weren't and that we're even questionable associations to begin with.

534
01:52:25,680 --> 01:52:37,680
And while I was doing that story, this fellow who was yelling at me, I like to joke he sounded exactly like Walter Mathau over the telephone. By the way, he's still alive. He's about 101 years old.

535
01:52:37,680 --> 01:52:47,680
So while I'm running him down as a scientist, that's arguing evidence that maybe he understands nutrition and diet far better than I do.

536
01:52:47,680 --> 01:53:03,680
And while I was interviewing him, this Walter Mathau character, it was clearly the, you know, I had spent 10 years of my life studying bad science was clear this guy was one of the worst scientists I'd ever interviewed in my life in the bottom five, at least.

537
01:53:03,680 --> 01:53:16,680
And I thought I had interviewed the worst. And he took credit not just for getting Americans to eat less salt, but eat less fat as well for the low fat diet we had all been on since 1984.

538
01:53:16,680 --> 01:53:26,680
So at one point, I called on my editor and I said, look, you know, if this guy was involved in this controversy, the fat controversy in any way, fat story, there's got to be a story there.

539
01:53:26,680 --> 01:53:34,680
You know, the message from Nobel dreams and bad science was that bad scientists never get the right answer.

540
01:53:34,680 --> 01:53:45,680
You know, it's just it's too hard to get the right answer for you to go in being sloppy and slip shot and lazy and ambitious and get it right. Nature isn't that kind.

541
01:53:45,680 --> 01:53:52,680
So I said, you know, when I'm done writing about salt, I'm going to write about fat. I have no idea what the story is. I've been eating. I've been living in L.A.

542
01:53:52,680 --> 01:54:02,680
You know, eating my egg whites and, you know, probably a 15 percent fat diet. Dean Ornish would have been proud of me.

543
01:54:02,680 --> 01:54:12,680
But if the dogma was based in any substantive way on this fellow's work, there's a story there. And I spent a year writing that piece.

544
01:54:12,680 --> 01:54:25,680
I interviewed 145 researchers and administrators for one magazine article and, you know, the big fat lie.

545
01:54:26,680 --> 01:54:36,680
No, this was the soft science of dietary fat. So this was the salt story was called the political science of salt, political in parentheses.

546
01:54:36,680 --> 01:54:42,680
And the fat story was called the soft science of dietary fat soft in parentheses.

547
01:54:42,680 --> 01:54:48,680
They both won National Association of Science Writers Science and Society Awards.

548
01:54:48,680 --> 01:54:58,680
What made you decide to go even further and write what would become perhaps the biggest and most controversial piece you wrote, at least in the newspaper?

549
01:54:58,680 --> 01:55:02,680
I believe it was for the Times magazine, wasn't it?

550
01:55:02,680 --> 01:55:16,680
Yeah, New York Times magazine. I wanted to write a book when I was done with the two science articles on whatever was happening in medical science that could lead to these kinds of mistakes.

551
01:55:16,680 --> 01:55:24,680
Remember, my obsession is pathological science. The nutrition aspect of it is just an interesting vehicle through which to explore it.

552
01:55:24,680 --> 01:55:33,680
I realize that if I did a book then I would go broke. I was married. I had responsibilities.

553
01:55:33,680 --> 01:55:42,680
Remember, I had come out forty thousand dollars in debt just doing the Cold Fusion book. It was clear I didn't work fast and I didn't want to work fast.

554
01:55:42,680 --> 01:56:00,680
And that I would not be able to get an advance large enough to cover the time it would take to do the book. So I was living in New York. I was having lunch once a month with an editor from the New York Times magazine because among other things, we shared an affinity for the same local French cafe in the village.

555
01:56:01,680 --> 01:56:09,680
And we would talk about story ideas and we decided it might be a good idea to ask the question what caused the obesity epidemic.

556
01:56:09,680 --> 01:56:19,680
And I said to this guy when I was reporting the dietary fat story for science, I had met up with an administrator from the NIH who said, you know, it's interesting.

557
01:56:19,680 --> 01:56:27,680
We told people to go on low fat diets in 1984. We assumed we really didn't have the evidence to support the heart disease connection.

558
01:56:27,680 --> 01:56:38,680
And the message of my story is they never got that evidence. But we thought if nothing else, we'd be telling people to avoid the densest calories in the diet. So if they avoided fat, they'd lose weight.

559
01:56:38,680 --> 01:56:48,680
And that would take care of the if you know obesity and overweight are the greatest risk factors for heart disease. And he said, lo and behold, now we have an obesity epidemic.

560
01:56:48,680 --> 01:57:04,680
And apparently people stopped eating fat and eating more carbohydrates and that got them fatter. So I always had this two hypotheses for what caused the obesity epidemic, which you can see in the data begins somewhere between 1978, 1991.

561
01:57:04,680 --> 01:57:14,680
And it coincides with two fundamental changes in the American diet. One was the low fat. The embracing of the idea that a low fat diet is a heart healthy diet.

562
01:57:14,680 --> 01:57:23,680
So carbohydrates in general go from being considered inherently fattening, which is sort of the conventional wisdom up till the 1960s.

563
01:57:23,680 --> 01:57:34,680
And then they get transformed into heart healthy diet foods. And you may be too young to remember this, but we all stopped eating butter and started having pasta and bagels every day.

564
01:57:35,680 --> 01:57:50,680
And lo and behold, everybody starts getting fatter. The other thing is high fructose corn syrup came in 1977 78 high fructose corn syrup 55 comes in, which can replace sugar in Coca Cola and Pepsi.

565
01:57:50,680 --> 01:58:03,680
And by 1984, it saturates the beverage industry. And this coincides with the beginning of the epidemic. And people like Michael Pollan had suggested that high fructose corn syrup was the cause of the epidemic.

566
01:58:03,680 --> 01:58:14,680
So we decided I would write an article about what might have caused the obesity epidemic was new enough then that people cared and this would be an important story.

567
01:58:14,680 --> 01:58:26,680
And in the course of writing that article, I came upon five studies that had been published that had been finished, but not yet published that all been discussed in conferences.

568
01:58:26,680 --> 01:58:42,680
So I could discuss them in the article, which had compared the Atkins diet, which is a low carbohydrate, high fat, eat as much as you want diet to the kind of low fat calorie restricted diet, the American Heart Association was pushing.

569
01:58:42,680 --> 01:58:53,680
And then all five trials, the Atkins diet, not only did people lose more weight, but their heart disease risk factors improved.

570
01:58:53,680 --> 01:59:07,680
So remember, I'm coming at this kind of from my program to think from a scientific perspective, I won't say that I'm coming from it to it as a scientist because I know people don't like to hear that from a journalist.

571
01:59:07,680 --> 01:59:13,680
There are two fundamental there are two hypotheses out there. One is that people get fat because they eat too much.

572
01:59:14,680 --> 01:59:18,680
And the other is that people get heart disease because they eat high fat foods.

573
01:59:18,680 --> 01:59:29,680
And now you want a diet trial where you compare a high fat eat as much as you want diet to a low fat calorie restricted diet.

574
01:59:29,680 --> 01:59:38,680
And your two hypotheses would predict that the high fat diet, the Atkins diet, those patients would get fatter because they can eat as much as they want.

575
01:59:38,680 --> 01:59:45,680
And clearly they got fat to begin with because they eat too much and that they would have worse heart disease risk factors.

576
01:59:45,680 --> 01:59:49,680
And in both cases, a hypothesis failed to pan out.

577
01:59:49,680 --> 01:59:59,680
So from a scientific perspective, the first five clinical trials on low carb, high fat diets, actually, it was second through six.

578
01:59:59,680 --> 02:00:05,680
There was one earlier one that saw the same thing that no one discussed all refuted.

579
02:00:05,680 --> 02:00:09,680
Two of the fundamental hypotheses of modern nutrition science.

580
02:00:09,680 --> 02:00:13,680
How did how did you find these? I mean, I know one of them.

581
02:00:13,680 --> 02:00:19,680
One of these in there is the Minnesota Heart Study, which wasn't published until 1989, right?

582
02:00:19,680 --> 02:00:26,680
Yeah, no, this is these are the clinical trials. So this is Eric Westman's first trial at Duke.

583
02:00:26,680 --> 02:00:32,680
There was a group at the VA Hospital in Pennsylvania that was doing a trial.

584
02:00:32,680 --> 02:00:37,680
There was along some researchers. Why weren't they published?

585
02:00:37,680 --> 02:00:41,680
They just hadn't been published yet. They had been finished.

586
02:00:41,680 --> 02:00:54,680
And the research we're talking about then once I did my article, it made it both more important for them to get published and simultaneously harder for them to get published because nobody wanted to hear.

587
02:00:54,680 --> 02:01:01,680
They wanted to see what these people really had, but not actually have to publish what these people really had.

588
02:01:01,680 --> 02:01:05,680
But over the next two or three years, they all came out in the journals.

589
02:01:05,680 --> 02:01:12,680
How did you sort of come to grips with this? This is now challenging your own beliefs.

590
02:01:12,680 --> 02:01:16,680
Presumably you had believed that this low fat diet was healthier.

591
02:01:16,680 --> 02:01:22,680
Had you ever struggled with your weight? Yeah.

592
02:01:22,680 --> 02:01:32,680
Well, remember, I was a college football player. So in college, I tried to be as heavy as humanly possible and eating constantly.

593
02:01:32,680 --> 02:01:46,680
I don't know if you did this in college, but we would go out at the eleven o'clock at night to Elsie's, a diner across the street from the dorm and eat a thousand calories or fifteen hundred calories worth of the biggest sandwiches they had, and then go home and go to bed.

594
02:01:47,680 --> 02:01:54,680
Anyway, I could get up to 240. My boxing weight was 212.

595
02:01:54,680 --> 02:02:01,680
And once I turned 30 and simultaneously had moved to California, I just started drifting upward.

596
02:02:01,680 --> 02:02:11,680
While I was reporting the science article, I was simultaneously doing a piece for Discover magazine on the mathematics of the stock market.

597
02:02:11,680 --> 02:02:32,680
So I was up at MIT interviewing an economist who ran the laboratory for financial engineering up there about his research, trying to establish whether people like Warren Buffett are brilliant or just lucky, which is an interesting question because you're looking for the signal of talent over the signal of luck, over the background of luck.

598
02:02:32,680 --> 02:02:37,680
And you don't, of course, fully understand your background.

599
02:02:38,680 --> 02:02:48,680
So we got to talking about good science and bad science. I told him about the dietary fat article I was writing, and he said, oh, well, if you're doing a story on fat, you got to try Atkins.

600
02:02:48,680 --> 02:03:01,680
He said his collaborator, Warden's father, lost 200 pounds on Atkins. And this fellow at MIT is an Asian American. And he said he gave up, basically gave up white rice and lost 40 pounds.

601
02:03:01,680 --> 02:03:14,680
So I went back to LA where I was living. At that point, I was unmarried. I, my parents had passed away. I had no children. If I killed myself on Atkins, the only one who might care were my cats.

602
02:03:14,680 --> 02:03:28,680
And so I did add as an experiment and lost 25 pounds in six weeks. And then like everyone else, I sort of drifted off the diet by the time I started this New York Times magazine piece.

603
02:03:28,680 --> 02:03:46,680
But if you go back to read the New York Times magazine article, there's a line in it that says, you know, overweight, of course, is caused by taking in more calories and you expand, which today I think is a meaningless statement and both wrong and meaningless.

604
02:03:46,680 --> 02:04:00,680
The, there were a lot of ways I had already, because of my research on the dietary fat story, I could already accept the idea that these diets would not raise the risk of heart disease.

605
02:04:00,680 --> 02:04:14,680
It was clear to me the dietary fat story was un-compelling at best. And there was no compelling evidence to avoid saturated fats.

606
02:04:14,680 --> 02:04:34,680
The question about the fundamental cause of obesity and how best to regulate weight was something I didn't really understand when I did that article. But that article will be, you know, exceedingly controversial article on the front page of the New York Times magazine will indeed get you a large book advance if the subject's one of, you know, natural interests to readers.

607
02:04:34,680 --> 02:04:45,680
It did get me a large book advance. People like to say that that's the only reason I came to the controversial conclusions I did, because it would sell more books.

608
02:04:45,680 --> 02:04:55,680
They don't realize that a large advance in New York was enough to live for four years and the book took me five years.

609
02:04:55,680 --> 02:05:04,680
Anyway, so that was it. That's when I started the research for Good Calories, Bad Calories and got obsessed with that story.

610
02:05:04,680 --> 02:05:13,680
And how did your thinking of the nuance around this topic evolve during the writing of Good Calories, Bad Calories, which I think came out in 07, right?

611
02:05:13,680 --> 02:05:23,680
Right. I mean, it's still evolving. That's what's so bizarre about this is I still wake up at three in the morning thinking, why didn't I say that 13 years ago?

612
02:05:24,680 --> 02:05:37,680
Because so there's these two issues, right? Which I mean, I don't think we'll have time to go into both of them. The one being the saturated fat issue, which is that dietary saturated fat drives atherosclerosis.

613
02:05:37,680 --> 02:05:52,680
And the other being the cause of obesity being calorie imbalance. And you kind of go after both of these in parallel, but they're really different.

614
02:05:52,680 --> 02:05:56,680
One, they're not mutually exclusive.

615
02:05:56,680 --> 02:05:59,680
Right. Well, but they're related.

616
02:05:59,680 --> 02:06:01,680
They're very related. Yes.

617
02:06:01,680 --> 02:06:16,680
And that's the issue. So the diet, if you know, the dietary heart story was that we get heart disease because of the dietary fat, saturated fat content of the diet, elevating LDL cholesterol.

618
02:06:16,680 --> 02:06:21,680
And here are a guy like Atkins comes along and says, well, look, don't need carbohydrates.

619
02:06:21,680 --> 02:06:31,680
So if you want to minimize your risk of heart disease by the dietary fat store, you avoid fats, saturated fats. You replace them with carbohydrates back then.

620
02:06:31,680 --> 02:06:38,680
Now they say monounsaturated or unsaturated fats. And you're now eating a carbohydrate rich diet.

621
02:06:38,680 --> 02:06:47,680
And in theory, you're going to minimize your risk of heart disease. The flip side was that carbohydrates are fat.

622
02:06:47,680 --> 02:06:54,680
That's the simplest way to describe what's now called the carbohydrate insulin model to those of us who gain weight easily.

623
02:06:54,680 --> 02:07:01,680
It's a carbohydrate to do it. And we can eat carbs. But if you don't eat carbs, what are you going to replace those with?

624
02:07:01,680 --> 02:07:07,680
And your choices are protein and fat and protein usually comes with fat attached and real foods.

625
02:07:07,680 --> 02:07:14,680
And so you're going to increase your fat consumption one way or the other. And now you're eating a diet. Then theory is supposed to kill you.

626
02:07:14,680 --> 02:07:20,680
And that was the one of the many arguments against Atkins was it's going to trigger heart disease and you're going to drop dead.

627
02:07:20,680 --> 02:07:25,680
When I first tried it as an experiment, I was kept waiting to drop dead. And I'm still waiting.

628
02:07:25,680 --> 02:07:34,680
I mean, I still have a piece of bacon and or a piece of, you know, patter butter and I wait for my heart to blow up.

629
02:07:34,680 --> 02:07:42,680
So one of the issues I had to deal with in the book is is how did we come to believe that dietary fats problem?

630
02:07:43,680 --> 02:07:55,680
So the first third of the book is the evolution of the it's the soft science of dietary fat at what length that how did we how did this theory evolve?

631
02:07:55,680 --> 02:08:02,680
What was the real data? What were the problems with the data? You know, why is it likely wrong?

632
02:08:02,680 --> 02:08:08,680
And then the second part of the book is as doing the research, I realized that there had always been a competing hypothesis,

633
02:08:08,680 --> 02:08:16,680
which is that the chronic diseases that associate with modern diets and lifestyles are driven by the carbohydrate content of the diet.

634
02:08:16,680 --> 02:08:29,680
So this started as a British hypothesis, British nutritionists, and then it should have embraced in the 1960s, the research by people like Jerry Reven and others on insulin resistance.

635
02:08:29,680 --> 02:08:38,680
And all of that targeted the quality and the type of carbohydrates reading the glycemic index and the fructose content.

636
02:08:38,680 --> 02:08:49,680
And I didn't know anything about that when I started this research. But by the time and so the first third of good calories, bad calories is the deconstruction of the fat hypothesis.

637
02:08:49,680 --> 02:08:55,680
The second third is the replacement with a carbohydrate centric hypothesis.

638
02:08:55,680 --> 02:09:13,680
And then the third third of the second half of the book actually is this question of obesity, because it's clear that whatever cause obesity is so closely associated our disease and diabetes type two diabetes, that whatever makes us fat also causes these chronic diseases that associate with us.

639
02:09:13,680 --> 02:09:27,680
And the question is, what makes us fat? And now I doing the research, I also came upon a whole other stream of research that had kind of been ignored.

640
02:09:27,680 --> 02:09:39,680
First, by pre World War Two European researchers saying obesity is not an energy balance problem. It's not caused by people eating too much. It's a hormonal regulatory disorder.

641
02:09:39,680 --> 02:09:50,680
And then post World War Two by people studying primarily the science of hunger, saying in effect hunger is caused by fuel availability and periphery.

642
02:09:50,680 --> 02:10:02,680
So if you have enough fuel, if your liver thinks there's enough fuel available, then you're not going to be hungry. And when your liver starts thinking fuel is being crimped, then it'll release inhibitions on food seeking behavior.

643
02:10:02,680 --> 02:10:13,680
And that work done by people in this field of physiological psychology all implicated insulin as the hormone determining fuel availability, the primary hormone.

644
02:10:13,680 --> 02:10:28,680
And then there was also, and this, I think, is what gets me most beginning around 1930, until 1930, virtually no one studied fat tissue.

645
02:10:28,680 --> 02:10:35,680
It wasn't it was a there were the been all these sort of burgeoning fields of physiology and endocrinology. Nobody really cared.

646
02:10:35,680 --> 02:10:44,680
The assumption was it was inert. It was for padding and cushioning. And if you starve people, somehow the fat tissue would shrink.

647
02:10:44,680 --> 02:10:51,680
Then you get this revolution beginning and they had no way to study fat tissue or fatty accumulation.

648
02:10:51,680 --> 02:11:01,680
And then beginning in 1933 with this work of this German emigre Schoenheimer working at Columbia, you start having people studying fat tissue.

649
02:11:01,680 --> 02:11:07,680
They become aware that mobilization deposition goes into fat goes on constantly.

650
02:11:07,680 --> 02:11:16,680
Like even when you're in between meals or starving, your body is still depositing calories as fat and mobilizing calories as fat.

651
02:11:16,680 --> 02:11:24,680
And through the 1940s and 50s, they begin to work out the details as more and more tools become available to study this problem.

652
02:11:24,680 --> 02:11:41,680
And by the mid 1960s, you have very well established science of what we could call intermediary metabolism, which is what the researchers, what your body does with the foods, the proteins, fats and carbohydrates after you eat them.

653
02:11:41,680 --> 02:11:50,680
And then what your body continues to do to make fuel available as necessary to your body. And all of this is left out of the science of obesity.

654
02:11:51,680 --> 02:12:04,680
As soon as the obesity researchers start saying we've demonstrated that obesity is caused by energy balance, imbalance, the in political way of saying that is people eat too much.

655
02:12:04,680 --> 02:12:15,680
That's a fact of life. We can see it in our animal models because when we create an obese animal model, it tends to be what they call hyperphagia, which is very hungry.

656
02:12:15,680 --> 02:12:20,680
So we have an association between hunger and obesity and we assume causality.

657
02:12:20,680 --> 02:12:28,680
And they never actually, they just kind of ignore the entire science of fat metabolism.

658
02:12:28,680 --> 02:12:36,680
And even to this day, when I try to make that point, it's excruciatingly hard to, nobody wants to hear it.

659
02:12:36,680 --> 02:12:39,680
Nobody wants to deal with it.

660
02:12:40,680 --> 02:12:44,680
And if I had to prove it to an editor, I could.

661
02:12:44,680 --> 02:12:53,680
Ideally, I would have the fact checker fly out to my office at Oakland and say, let's go through these textbooks from 1965 onward.

662
02:12:53,680 --> 02:13:02,680
And I'll show you the complete and utter absence of any discussion of the science of fat metabolism, fat storage from the obesity discussion.

663
02:13:03,680 --> 02:13:15,680
And from the 1960s on where the obesity researchers are dominant, well, obesity research in the 1960s is dominated by psychiatrists and psychologists trying to get fat people to eat less.

664
02:13:15,680 --> 02:13:24,680
People like Mickey Stunkard, who was a wonderful man, but his expertise with psychology and this idea that obesity is a hormonal.

665
02:13:25,680 --> 02:13:33,680
Disregulation of fat storage, fatty acid oxidation and storage, a fuel partitioning disorder gets left out of the field.

